WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.320
My name is Grant Fleming, and I'm a data scientist at Elder Research, where I work on data science

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:17.320
consulting projects with various public sector clients.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:23.160
And in that work, along with a lot of the work that I'm doing outside of work work,

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:28.760
I'm having to wrestle with the issue of fairness and data science, specifically things like

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:33.959
how do we make sure that the predictions being generated by our models are fair?

00:00:33.959 --> 00:00:39.279
How do we make sure we're actually recording the correct information in our data and not

00:00:39.279 --> 00:00:42.160
leaving certain important factors out?

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:48.720
And if we suspect that something may have snuck in our model, how do we make sure that

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:54.459
we're able to detect that element before we deploy our model and cause harm intentionally?

00:00:54.459 --> 00:00:58.160
Because as we've seen probably in some of the news over the past few years, this is

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:02.939
an issue that's, if not become more widespread, become more widely known.

00:01:02.939 --> 00:01:09.820
For example, in 2018, Joy Buolamwini and her research team at MIT published the GenderShades

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:18.339
work that they did on facial recognition algorithms from companies like Amazon, IBM, and others.

00:01:18.339 --> 00:01:25.419
And in this work, they found out that these facial recognition algorithms were actually

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:31.279
having much higher error rates, detecting darker skin faces versus lighter skin faces.

00:01:31.279 --> 00:01:36.839
And that obviously is something that we would not want to see in any sort of fair model.

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:43.000
Similarly, we saw something similar in 2019 in the healthcare sector, where an algorithm

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:50.559
furnished to hospitals throughout the US, which was tasked with helping to allocate

00:01:50.559 --> 00:01:57.300
treatment to patients within the hospitals, was systematically underestimating the healthcare

00:01:57.300 --> 00:02:03.180
needs for black patients relative to white patients or patients from other ethnic groups.

00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:09.580
Again, likely a case of unintended bias, but nonetheless, something that led to harms in

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:11.740
the real world.

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:16.000
And I could spend the rest of the session talking about these issues across the various

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.279
different examples, which I'm not including, but that's not productive.

00:02:20.279 --> 00:02:24.539
Maybe what's more productive then is coming to an understanding of why this is actually

00:02:24.539 --> 00:02:26.100
happening.

00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:32.259
So from my perspective, at least, it seems like this is in large part the result of us

00:02:32.259 --> 00:02:37.899
as data scientists thinking that our tools alone, the technical tools, the code and the

00:02:37.899 --> 00:02:44.899
data and the models that we were able to build are enough to solve these complex social problems.

00:02:44.899 --> 00:02:49.699
Like duct tape, we use them wherever we can to fix whatever we can.

00:02:49.699 --> 00:02:56.080
And some situations are helped by duct tape, but duct tape cannot alone solve everything.

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:00.440
I think that's a good metaphor here for how we should think about it.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:02.559
Or maybe how we do think about it.

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:08.440
How we should think about it instead is our toolkit is not duct tape that should be used

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:13.880
wildly wherever we can, but rather our toolkit is one that, along with people who have the

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:21.020
subject matter and lived expertise in the areas that we seem to operate in, they, along

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:27.500
with us, can lay brick by brick a solution to a problem or at least get closer to solving

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:28.699
it.

00:03:28.699 --> 00:03:30.740
And this is twofold.

00:03:30.740 --> 00:03:35.779
We from them can get a greater appreciation for the factors that can't be encoded in our

00:03:35.779 --> 00:03:41.740
data or aren't encoded in our data, but are nonetheless relevant to our work.

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:50.440
And they, in turn, can help us to better diagnose issues within our models before they're deployed.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:52.559
Sounds good, but how do we actually do this?

00:03:52.559 --> 00:03:56.399
How do we actually do responsible, ethical, trustworthy, however you want to call it,

00:03:56.399 --> 00:03:58.520
data science in practice?

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:03.320
It's the million dollar question, and a number of researchers are working to try and answer

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:04.320
this.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:09.360
And to my reading, it seems like they've coalesced around the three main factors that go into

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:14.979
making a data science project, we'll just say a responsible data science project.

00:04:14.979 --> 00:04:19.100
Those being, first, fairness in procedures.

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:24.059
So basically, was the project designed in such a way that it can be conducted fairly?

00:04:24.059 --> 00:04:30.179
Did it include a diverse range of voices and all relevant stakeholders?

00:04:30.179 --> 00:04:32.519
Next would be fairness in predictions.

00:04:32.519 --> 00:04:38.019
So when the model was actually built, does the model perform equally well across different

00:04:38.019 --> 00:04:39.839
groups within the data?

00:04:39.839 --> 00:04:42.779
And the final one being fairness and outcomes.

00:04:42.779 --> 00:04:49.799
So once the actual process of the model is set in stone and is more or less fair, and

00:04:49.799 --> 00:04:57.920
even if we get relative fairness in our predictions, does the impact of those predictions actually

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:00.399
improve fairness in the real world?

00:05:00.399 --> 00:05:04.380
Are the impacts of those predictions equitable?

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:08.600
So fairness in outcomes, obviously, is something that's a little bit harder to measure, maybe

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.959
than the other two, but we'll attempt to talk about it at least a little bit over the course

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:15.359
of this presentation.

00:05:15.359 --> 00:05:20.640
And the way we'll move forward with this is going through each of the three of these in

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:25.600
more detail, and we'll go through this in the context of a practical example.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:31.019
But hopefully, by maintaining all three of these within our projects, if not doing our

00:05:31.079 --> 00:05:37.640
projects in a way that is perfectly fair, we will get closer to a fair, responsible

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:39.279
data science.

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:44.239
So let's begin with fairness in procedures.

00:05:44.239 --> 00:05:49.239
And where better to start thinking about that than ensuring inclusion.

00:05:49.239 --> 00:05:55.000
If you don't have a diverse perspective or diverse group of perspectives on your project,

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.920
in all likelihood, something could slip through that would cause an unintended harm when your

00:06:00.019 --> 00:06:01.019
model was deployed.

00:06:01.019 --> 00:06:06.779
This is especially relevant for someone like me, who not only is a consultant, who's often

00:06:06.779 --> 00:06:12.100
coming into a data science project in a subject matter context where I have less expertise

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:18.500
than maybe some of the people I'm working with, but also because I'm a white man.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:27.299
And that bears with it certain biases, some of them benign, some of them harmful, in how

00:06:27.299 --> 00:06:30.480
I see the world and operate within it.

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:36.000
And it's important for me and the people I work with on projects and the clients I work

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:42.559
with that those biases are checked by the views that other people can bring to the table.

00:06:42.559 --> 00:06:48.799
And I think critically, this is something that is worthy in all projects and besides

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:51.679
being the right thing to do.

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:54.279
Next though, would be reproducible code.

00:06:54.279 --> 00:06:58.820
We don't want code that just runs on our own machines.

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:04.380
This is maybe easier said than done, but there are fortunately within the R ecosystem a number

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:06.540
of packages available for this.

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:12.059
I won't go too much into detail on what those are because so many other people have already

00:07:12.059 --> 00:07:13.899
spoken in depth about these.

00:07:13.899 --> 00:07:16.040
I'll reference two of them here.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:19.839
The first would probably be Dr. Anna Cristalli.

00:07:19.839 --> 00:07:24.540
She has a great talk called Putting the R into Reproducible Research, which you can

00:07:24.540 --> 00:07:25.540
find by Googling.

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:27.339
It should come up.

00:07:27.339 --> 00:07:32.140
And then another person, Karthik Ram, delivered a talk at the previous RStudio conference

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:33.140
in 2019.

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:34.140
Google that.

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:35.140
You should find it.

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:38.940
I don't remember the title, but between the two of them, they covered a lot of really

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:43.540
great materials for doing reproducible work within R.

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:48.339
But back to fairness and procedures, finally, to wrap this all up, we want to make sure

00:07:48.339 --> 00:07:53.760
that we document everything we do and every decision we make in the same way that we want

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:57.260
to have our code be reproducible by technical people.

00:07:57.260 --> 00:08:02.320
We also want non-technical people who may not be able to actually access our code directly

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:06.920
to be able to pour through our results in a way that's easy for them to interpret and

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:09.519
that they can actually evaluate.

00:08:09.519 --> 00:08:15.000
And the Google Brain Ethical AI team has done a lot of good work on this.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.459
They've come up with data sheets, model cards, and audit reports.

00:08:19.459 --> 00:08:26.100
So three different sort of documentation modalities that you can all think of as nutrition labels,

00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:29.100
I guess, for each part of the project.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:34.460
And even though we don't yet have any way to do these within R, hopefully soon there

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:39.099
will be some sort of R markdown templates that make this easier for us.

00:08:39.099 --> 00:08:42.619
I'm certainly on my own end trying to put together a package for it, and we'll hopefully

00:08:42.619 --> 00:08:45.280
have some more updates on that in the future.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:49.320
Point being, though, if anyone wants to look at good examples for these, they can Google

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:55.679
the research done by Timnit Gebru, Debra Raji, and Megan Mitchell.

00:08:55.679 --> 00:09:00.280
And for good examples of model cards, I specifically definitely recommend looking up the TensorFlow

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:02.200
model card toolkit.

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:07.640
So TensorFlow already has built-in functionality for building model cards, and they have some

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:13.099
good examples for that there of things that we may want to track in our own work.

00:09:13.099 --> 00:09:18.299
With that being done, you have a relatively fair process in place.

00:09:18.299 --> 00:09:23.940
And so you're in good shape to start now thinking about fairness and predictions, starting with

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:26.219
predicting accurately.

00:09:26.219 --> 00:09:30.739
This doesn't need a whole lot of development, but I include this here to make sure to point

00:09:30.739 --> 00:09:37.219
out that if you do not have high predictive performance overall on your model, by no conception

00:09:37.219 --> 00:09:38.260
can it be fair.

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:43.760
Even if you perform equally across groups, getting a 10% level of performance across

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:49.080
all of them is meaningless, and that's going to do you and the people this model is hoping

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:52.320
to serve no good whatsoever.

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:58.119
But more subtle and probably more relevant to the work we do is predicting equally.

00:09:58.119 --> 00:10:03.159
And to explore this in practical detail and how we can actually work on this in our own

00:10:03.159 --> 00:10:08.820
projects, we're going to go through an example with the Compass Recidivism dataset.

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:15.299
So this is a dataset released by the public interest group ProPublica, and what it tracks

00:10:15.299 --> 00:10:22.219
is demographic and criminal records information of defendants.

00:10:22.219 --> 00:10:27.059
And the goal of this is to take all this information and use it to predict whether these defendants

00:10:27.059 --> 00:10:30.599
will commit another crime in the next two years.

00:10:30.599 --> 00:10:35.219
Because of the demographic information within this data, it's often used as sort of the

00:10:35.219 --> 00:10:42.260
iris or titanic dataset for fairness methods and evaluation of fairness maintaining approaches

00:10:42.260 --> 00:10:48.020
within data science, as we're about to do here, and as I already did here.

00:10:48.020 --> 00:10:54.659
So on this plot, we can see two different bars, one for the accuracy of a logistic regression

00:10:54.659 --> 00:10:57.099
and one for the accuracy of a random forest model.

00:10:57.599 --> 00:11:01.440
And again, these are taking demographic and criminal history features and predicting a

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:07.479
binary yes, no, will commit a crime, will not commit a crime within two years.

00:11:07.479 --> 00:11:13.640
We can see that they perform roughly the same, nothing really jumping out here, which is

00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:16.880
why maybe we want to dig a little deeper.

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:19.359
Maybe we can look at per group metrics.

00:11:19.359 --> 00:11:25.000
So in this case, instead of just looking at overall model performance, we'll still look

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:30.260
at the performance of one model versus the other, but we're going to look at it with

00:11:30.260 --> 00:11:35.500
respect to a protected feature or sensitive feature, in this case, race, and then the

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:41.020
protected groups, aka the levels of that feature, which in this case would be Hispanic, other

00:11:41.020 --> 00:11:43.739
Caucasian or African-American.

00:11:43.739 --> 00:11:47.900
And already here, we can see that there's some differences or disparities in performance

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:54.559
coming to the fore, with African-Americans specifically, the model getting the lowest

00:11:54.559 --> 00:11:58.840
accuracy for African-Americans relative to other groups.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:05.000
This is already a pretty compelling result, I think, goes to show that overall metrics

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:10.760
alone are not enough to be able to identify when you may have some issues or unfairness

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:15.760
in your model, but we still don't necessarily know why these disparities exist.

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:20.380
These disparities have to be in part due to different rates of error, and we don't know

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:24.820
whether that's more false positives or more false negatives for the different groups.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:28.739
So let's actually look at plots of error direction.

00:12:28.739 --> 00:12:35.260
And here's where we start to see the real compelling causes come to the fore here, with

00:12:35.260 --> 00:12:41.500
in this case, the model hitting a almost four times higher false positive rate error for

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:49.440
African-Americans than Caucasians, and similarly high rates for other non-Caucasian groups.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:54.000
This is clearly an issue of bias, and if we were not to rectify this or communicate this

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:00.280
to our clients or the non-technical people we're working with in this project, and we

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:06.000
were to just put a stamp on this and let it go, in the real world, this would perpetuate

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:12.500
all sorts of biases that would be harmful, and we don't want that.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:17.460
So to get a better context to that, before we actually communicate those conclusions,

00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:21.900
maybe we want to be able to say, okay, we've made every comparison between every different

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:26.979
group, so Caucasians with African-Americans, Caucasians with Hispanics, and maybe we care

00:13:26.979 --> 00:13:31.619
specifically about the relative performance, so we want to look at the percent differences.

00:13:31.619 --> 00:13:33.099
That's where fairness metrics come in.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:36.760
They don't measure absolute performance, they measure relative.

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:41.840
When we look at it in this plot here, it's still the same y-axis, still the same x-axis,

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:47.359
but now we get the percentages of false positive rates for each group relative to the privileged

00:13:47.359 --> 00:13:49.679
group, Caucasians.

00:13:49.679 --> 00:13:54.919
And again, we can see here that there's quite a lot of disparity.

00:13:54.919 --> 00:13:56.559
Why though?

00:13:56.559 --> 00:14:01.599
What is it in the features that are going into the model that are causing these disparities

00:14:01.599 --> 00:14:03.479
to exist?

00:14:03.479 --> 00:14:08.500
It's hard to get at causality at any point within data science, but if we want to at

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:13.859
least understand more about how the features impact these predictions differently, we're

00:14:13.859 --> 00:14:16.900
going to want to look at interpretability methods.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:22.580
These are often explained in the context of the black box, hence the image on the right.

00:14:22.580 --> 00:14:27.780
What they allow us to do is open this black box, because a lot of these interpretability

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:32.599
methods are model agnostic, and they can be used even on models like XGBoost or Random

00:14:32.599 --> 00:14:39.119
Forest to generate the sort of explanations, maybe not quite to the same level of fidelity,

00:14:39.119 --> 00:14:44.559
but approximately, that we would get from a linear model, like linear regression or

00:14:44.559 --> 00:14:47.119
something like logistic regression.

00:14:47.119 --> 00:14:51.000
I'm not going to go through these in detail within this presentation, because the visuals

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.919
for them are a little complex and we don't have a lot of time, but I will mention that

00:14:54.919 --> 00:14:59.219
they come in two main varieties, the first being global methods, which explain the average

00:14:59.219 --> 00:15:00.619
effect of features globally.

00:15:00.619 --> 00:15:05.580
You can think of this as like the coefficient of a regression, and if you want to read more

00:15:05.580 --> 00:15:09.299
about them, you can look up something like permutation feature importance, which ought

00:15:09.299 --> 00:15:14.539
to be well known to a number of people, partial dependence plots, or individual conditional

00:15:14.539 --> 00:15:17.260
expectation plots.

00:15:17.260 --> 00:15:23.419
We can also look at something in the category of the local methods, and this could be say

00:15:23.419 --> 00:15:29.599
LIME or Shapley values or derivatives of either of those, and these are really powerful

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:36.479
because they allow us to say for an individual prediction on one observation, each feature

00:15:36.479 --> 00:15:41.239
value, we can quantify the exact amount that it contributed to the prediction.

00:15:41.239 --> 00:15:45.119
So if someone were to ask, hey, why did I get this specific classification from your

00:15:45.119 --> 00:15:46.119
model?

00:15:46.119 --> 00:15:50.640
You could tell them this feature contributed this much, this contributed this much, etc.

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:53.820
A lot of useful explanation there.

00:15:53.820 --> 00:15:57.500
Hopefully this is something that we can end up applying to most of our models, and it's

00:15:57.500 --> 00:16:03.219
certainly a set of techniques which are well developed within the R package ecosystem currently.

00:16:03.219 --> 00:16:09.820
The IML package by Christoph Molnar is available, and I use it in my work and I think it's fantastic,

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:16.859
but there's also the VIP and DALEX, D-A-L-E-X, I believe, packages which include a number

00:16:16.859 --> 00:16:20.380
of interpretability methods as well.

00:16:21.119 --> 00:16:26.479
And that all about wraps up the fairness and prediction side, so again, if you're able

00:16:26.479 --> 00:16:30.960
in your own work to ensure those three main points are hit, then you're well on your way

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:34.719
to having more fair predictions.

00:16:34.719 --> 00:16:41.679
Which then leads us to the thorny issue and possible future-looking set of solutions for

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:48.679
fairness and outcomes, and why is this future-leaning, why is this a thorny set of issues?

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:55.380
Outcomes are all about the consequences and how we consider fairness in the context of

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:57.460
the real world.

00:16:57.460 --> 00:17:01.659
Because these outcomes and the impacts they have on people are not necessarily something

00:17:01.659 --> 00:17:07.420
that we can measure in the data, or at least can, or at least do measure in the data, it's

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:13.260
something that requires conversations not just with the people who maybe we're working

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:18.099
with who are non-technical, who have the subject matter expertise for the projects we're working

00:17:18.119 --> 00:17:22.359
on, but also the people impacted by the models.

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:27.280
And talking with all these different groups and coming up with some conception of fairness

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:35.520
to say, okay, maybe we're going to optimize for certain predictions despite these predictions

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:39.400
coming at a loss of predictive performance for our model, because ultimately that's the

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:43.680
equitable thing to do, that's something that's very project-specific.

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:49.619
It doesn't make a lot of sense for me or anyone else to give any sort of real definitive

00:17:49.619 --> 00:17:51.660
guidance on that.

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:56.859
And just for a little bit more detail, maybe an example to make this clear, you could think

00:17:56.859 --> 00:18:02.339
of fairness and outcomes as being relevant in a case where maybe we're deciding whether

00:18:02.339 --> 00:18:09.939
someone deserves a scholarship, binary yes-no, a yes would benefit someone who comes from

00:18:09.939 --> 00:18:14.199
maybe a more disadvantaged background, much more than someone who comes from a more privileged

00:18:14.199 --> 00:18:15.719
background.

00:18:15.719 --> 00:18:19.479
And again, that's not necessarily something we'd measure within our model.

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:23.520
But if it's something we want to try and work towards, then we need to make sure to mitigate

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:29.079
the bias that we see in our model in a specific way to serve that end.

00:18:29.079 --> 00:18:32.040
And that's where bias mitigation techniques come in.

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:37.239
And I have the star on the word there in the previous slide, because these techniques,

00:18:37.260 --> 00:18:42.660
they sometimes work well, they sometimes don't, but by and large, they all have trade-offs.

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:46.819
And that's because you're either modifying the data in the case of pre-processing that

00:18:46.819 --> 00:18:52.079
goes into your models, the model itself, or the predictions that come out of the model

00:18:52.079 --> 00:18:54.819
to reach some notion of fairness.

00:18:54.819 --> 00:19:00.500
And while that may improve that specific notion of fairness, you may see that there are losses

00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:04.339
in predictive performance or fairness across other dimensions.

00:19:04.439 --> 00:19:07.760
And to show this, we'll go back and look at the compass example.

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:14.560
So here, I have a plot, again, it shows protected groups on the y-axis and false positive rate

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:17.319
on the x-axis.

00:19:17.319 --> 00:19:21.040
But now we're looking, instead of at logistic regression and random forest, we're looking

00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:23.520
at just the random forest.

00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:28.599
But we're looking at two sets of predictions here, one where the prediction thresholds

00:19:28.599 --> 00:19:35.939
are all set at 0.5, for if you have a higher than 0.5, we'll predict that you will commit

00:19:35.939 --> 00:19:38.660
a crime, lower the opposite.

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:44.540
And one that's set to an optimal level for each class, such that it minimizes false positive

00:19:44.540 --> 00:19:45.540
rate.

00:19:45.540 --> 00:19:49.900
And we can see here that it does that well, all groups actually have a large decrease

00:19:49.900 --> 00:19:55.880
in false positive rate, which is great, at least relative to each other.

00:19:55.880 --> 00:20:01.219
We need to actually go back a few levels to look at the per group performance metrics

00:20:01.219 --> 00:20:05.219
on the absolute basis to see what happened there.

00:20:05.219 --> 00:20:10.420
And when we do that, unfortunately, we see that most of the gains in fairness that we

00:20:10.420 --> 00:20:17.420
made in that previous plot are actually due to the error rate, mostly increasing for the

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:22.859
groups, but increasing for the other groups more than it did for the African American

00:20:22.859 --> 00:20:23.859
group.

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:29.479
So basically, what happened here is the model said, OK, you want to make it more fair across

00:20:29.479 --> 00:20:35.160
groups for false positive rate, we'll make it so that the other groups have more error

00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:39.959
and make it so that the African American group, their error relative to the other groups is

00:20:39.959 --> 00:20:41.920
lower than it was originally.

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:47.439
Again, if fairness is our goal here, that's fine, that's not a bad result.

00:20:47.439 --> 00:20:51.520
However, it clearly did come with a trade off.

00:20:51.540 --> 00:20:56.140
And whenever we use these methods, this is just something we're going to have to consider.

00:20:56.140 --> 00:21:02.819
Lastly, for fairness and outcomes, we want to consider the possibility of algorithmic

00:21:02.819 --> 00:21:03.819
recourse.

00:21:03.819 --> 00:21:09.420
So if our models are making decisions about people, we don't want them to lose the ability

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:12.219
to actually have some influence over that decision.

00:21:12.219 --> 00:21:16.739
They should be able to appeal it, they should be able to ask for explanations as to why

00:21:16.739 --> 00:21:22.680
they were given that decision, and they should be given, if asked, or if they choose to ask,

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:24.880
recommendations for what they can do to change it.

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:30.319
For more info on this, I recommend looking at the work of Ruha Benjamin, William Isaac,

00:21:30.319 --> 00:21:31.319
or Shakir Mohammed.

00:21:31.319 --> 00:21:36.119
Google any of those names and you'll come up with a lot of good stuff.

00:21:36.119 --> 00:21:39.400
And at that point, you've hit fairness and outcomes.

00:21:39.400 --> 00:21:44.560
You've hit all three of the main notions of fairness that have come up across the research,

00:21:44.579 --> 00:21:51.300
and you're doing a solid job at doing data science more responsibly.

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:59.180
And fundamentally, that's great, because doing data science in this way is the right thing to do.

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:03.500
There's a lot of good moral justifications for why we should do our work with a greater

00:22:03.500 --> 00:22:08.859
conception for fairness and consider factors outside of the code and the data and the predictions

00:22:08.859 --> 00:22:11.099
that we normally deal with.

00:22:11.099 --> 00:22:16.280
Maybe as a profession, we should start thinking of ourselves not just as data scientists,

00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:20.719
but also ethnographers, sociologists, anthropologists.

00:22:20.719 --> 00:22:24.040
Not just thinking about it, though, actually getting that knowledge, and that's something

00:22:24.040 --> 00:22:26.000
we should seek out.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:32.880
But beyond being the morally right thing to do, I also want to make one more point.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:36.359
This is not just the right thing to do.

00:22:36.359 --> 00:22:42.699
Doing these practices and doing data science more responsibly in this way is doing better

00:22:42.699 --> 00:22:44.699
data science.

00:22:44.699 --> 00:22:50.140
By doing responsible data science, you'll build better models, you'll have less errors

00:22:50.140 --> 00:22:53.020
sneaking through to model deployment.

00:22:53.020 --> 00:22:58.099
And fundamentally, you'll be serving all the people that you're already serving much better

00:22:58.099 --> 00:23:02.540
than you are now, and with a greater eye to safety and fairness.

00:23:03.520 --> 00:23:07.479
If that's not worth doing, then I don't know what is.

00:23:07.479 --> 00:23:12.319
So what I have here to wrap up with are a few resources, additional links that people

00:23:12.319 --> 00:23:17.280
can look at, but I have a number of other resources in addition to code to generate

00:23:17.280 --> 00:23:20.439
those plots and do a few other analyses in the GitHub.

00:23:20.439 --> 00:23:23.000
So if you're interested, please do check that out.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:27.839
But otherwise, thanks for coming to the talk and for sitting here with me.

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:34.219
Hope to connect with you soon and see you using these techniques yourself.

00:23:34.219 --> 00:23:34.719
Best of luck.

